FOR THE YEARS ENDED

DECEMBER 31, 2013, 2012 AND 2011

, RESPECTIVELY. OUR

2013

EFFECTIVE TAX RATE IS LOWER THAN

2012

PRIMARILY DUE TO THE INCLUSION OF THE U.S. RESEARCH AND DEVELOPMENT TAX CREDIT (RESEARCH TAX CREDIT) IN 2013, WHICH WAS NOT AVAILABLE IN 2012, AND THE RECOGNITION OF PREVIOUSLY UNRECOGNIZED TAX BENEFITS AS A RESULT OF NEW REGULATIONS DESCRIBED BELOW. IN 2013, PRESIDENT OBAMA SIGNED INTO LAW THE AMERICAN TAXPAYER RELIEF ACT OF 2012 THAT RETROACTIVELY RENEWED THE RESEARCH TAX CREDIT FOR 2012 AND EXTENDED THE CREDIT THROUGH DECEMBER 31, 2013. AS TAX LAW CHANGES ARE RECOGNIZED IN THE PERIOD IN WHICH NEW LEGISLATION IS ENACTED, THE 2012 RESEARCH TAX CREDIT OF

$145

WAS RECORDED IN THE FIRST QUARTER OF 2013. OUR 2012 EFFECTIVE TAX RATE WAS HIGHER THAN 2011, PRIMARILY DUE TO TAX BENEFITS OF

$397

RECORDED IN 2011 AS A RESULT OF FEDERAL INCOME TAX AUDIT SETTLEMENTS IN ADDITION TO RESEARCH TAX CREDITS WHICH WERE NOT AVAILABLE IN 2012. THE RESEARCH TAX CREDIT EXPIRED ON DECEMBER 31, 2013. IF THE RESEARCH TAX CREDIT IS NOT EXTENDED THERE WOULD BE AN UNFAVORABLE IMPACT TO OUR 2014 EFFECTIVE INCOME TAX RATE.

ON SEPTEMBER 5, 2013, THE INTERNAL REVENUE SERVICE (IRS) ISSUED PROPOSED REGULATIONS THAT AMEND THE DEFINITION OF RESEARCH AND EXPERIMENTAL (R&E) EXPENDITURES. THE REGULATIONS PROVIDED CLARITY REGARDING THE CATEGORIES OF EXPENSE THAT CAN BE CONSIDERED WHEN COMPUTING THE RESEARCH TAX CREDIT. BASED UPON OUR ANALYSIS OF THE REGULATIONS,

$212

OF PREVIOUSLY UNRECOGNIZED TAX BENEFITS RELATED TO RESEARCH TAX CREDITS WERE RECORDED AS A REDUCTION TO TAX EXPENSE IN THE FOURTH QUARTER OF 2013.

